The two Poland
The European Parliament recently condemned the Polish government's attempt to strip Bronislaw Geremek of his parliamentary mandate.
Former leader of Solidarity, former political prisoner and former Foreign Minister - he led Poland's accession to NATO - Geremek refused to sign another statement asserting that he was not a secret police agent during the communist era.
European parliamentarians spoke of a "witch hunt" regarding the Polish government's conduct, and Geremek stated that the law on decommunization constitutes a threat to public freedoms.
In response, Polish Prime Minister Jaroslaw Kaczynski accused him of "harming the motherland" and of inciting anti-Polish sentiment.
The communists used the same words when Geremek criticized their abuse of power.
A constitutional court decision dated May 11 largely invalidated the decommunization law, allowing Geremek to retain his seat in the European Parliament, at least for now.
But this law fits within the broader policy of the Polish government, which has no other aim than to weaken the country's institutions and democratic fabric.
What is happening in Poland, the country where the collapse of communism began?
Every revolution goes through two phases: first a struggle for freedom, then a struggle for power.
The first is the emancipation of the human soul through which man expresses his best, while the second frees the worst: envy, intrigues, greed, suspicion, and the desire for revenge.
The revolution triggered by the Polish trade union Solidarity followed an unusual trajectory.
Solidarity, forced into the underground when martial law was declared in December 1981, survived seven years of repression to reemerge into the open in 1989, following the "perestroika" initiated by Gorbachev.
During the negotiations that ended the communist regime, Solidarity and the reformist wing of the communist government reached an agreement that paved the way for the peaceful dismantling of the communist dictatorship throughout the entire Soviet bloc.
Solidarity adopted a conciliatory attitude rather than revenge, preferring the idea of a Poland for all rather than a country divided between all-powerful winners and oppressed losers.
Since 1989, there have been changes in government, but the country has remained stable. The former communists themselves have accepted the rules of parliamentary democracy and the market economy.
But not everyone followed this path.
Today, Poland is governed by a coalition of post-Solidarity revenge-seekers, post-communist regional agitators, xenophobic and anti-Semitic groups, heirs to pre-war chauvinism, and circles surrounding Radio Maryja, the voice of ethno-clerical fundamentalism.
One can see everywhere alarming signs: the authority of the judiciary is undermined, the independence of the Constitutional Tribunal is questioned, civil servants are bought, and the role of the prosecutor is politicized.
Every day, social life is subjected to repressive regulation.
Why all of this?
Every revolution that succeeds has its winners and its losers.
The Polish revolution brought about public freedoms, but also increased crime, a market economy, as well as the risk of bankruptcy for companies and high unemployment, along with the emergence of a dynamic middle class, accompanied by a widening income gap.
It opened Poland to Europe, but it also instilled the fear of the foreigner and the fear of a mass Western cultural invasion.
For the losers of the 1989 Polish revolution, freedom comes with a lot of uncertainties.
In large companies, Solidarity workers have become the victims of the freedoms they won.
In the communist prison system, people were considered part of the state, but the state took care of them.
In a world of freedom, there is no one to take care of us.
It is within this atmosphere of anxiety that the current coalition governs, combining George Bush's conservative potion with Vladimir Putin's centralism.
Veterans of Solidarity believed that the end of the dictatorship would allow them to reach the heavens.
But the guilty among the communists were not punished, and the virtuous Solidarity activists were not rewarded.
Also, the feeling of injustice gave rise to resentment, envy, and a vengeful energy directed both against former enemies and old friends who seemed to be getting away with it.
The losers did not want to acknowledge that the conquest of freedom was the greatest achievement of Poland in 300 years.
For them, Poland remained a country governed by the communist security apparatus.
This Poland lacked a moral revolution that would ensure that crimes would not go unpunished, virtue would be rewarded, and injustices would be rectified.
After their victory in the 2005 general elections, the political parties of the losers chose a method: a major purge.
According to the initial estimates, the decommunization process should take 17 years and affect 700,000 people.
A list of names was found in the archives of the security services; it will be made public.
And the 700,000 people slated for decommunization must declare that they did not collaborate with the security services.
Those who refuse or make a false declaration must be dismissed and prohibited from practicing their profession for ten years.
