The cardinal Dziwisz of Kraków reminds us that there is no place "for revenge, vengeance, a lack of respect for human dignity, and baseless accusations."
Never since the fall of communism has a cardinal used such strong words.
Should this decommunization have taken place at the beginning of Poland's transformation? The aim of this peaceful revolution was freedom, sovereignty, and economic reforms, and not a hunt for suspected, proven or not, members of the secret police.
If this hunt had been organized in 1990, neither the economic reforms of Leszek Balcerowicz nor the establishment of the rule of law would have been possible.
And Poland would not be a member of NATO nor the European Union.
Today, two Poles face each other.
The Poland of suspicion, fear, and vengeance fights the Poland of hope, courage, and dialogue.
This Poland - made of openness and tolerance, that of John Paul II and Czesław Miłosz, of my friends from the underground and from prison - must prevail.
I believe the Poles will once again defend their right to be treated with dignity.
The decision of the constitutional court leaves hope that the second phase of the Polish revolution will not destroy what gave it birth, the will to freedom, nor what it has generated, a democratic state.
